  "prompt": "In reaction, [math]N_2 O_4\\to {2NO_2}_{(g)}[/math], what will be the value of [math]K_C[/math] at 35\u00b0 C if [math]N_2 O_4[/math] is dissociated to the extent of 20% under a pressure of 1 atmosphere?",
  "response": "Here's how to calculate Kc for the given reaction:\n\n**1. Set up an ICE Table**\n\nLet's use an ICE (Initial, Change, Equilibrium) table to track the partial pressures of the reactants and products:\n\n|                     | N\u2082O\u2084     | 2NO\u2082     |\n| ------------------- | -------- | -------- |\n| Initial (I)         | 1 atm     | 0 atm    |\n| Change (C)          | -0.20 atm | +0.40 atm |\n| Equilibrium (E)     | 0.80 atm     | 0.40 atm    |\n\n*   Since N\u2082O\u2084 dissociates to 20%, the change in pressure for N\u2082O\u2084 is -0.20 atm (20% of 1 atm).\n*   Because the stoichiometry of the reaction is 1 N\u2082O\u2084 to 2 NO\u2082, the change in pressure for NO\u2082 is +2 * 0.20 atm = +0.40 atm.\n*   The total pressure at equilibrium is [math]P_{N_2O_4} + P_{NO_2}=1.2 atm[/math]\n*   The mole fraction of N\u2082O\u2084 is [math]0.8/1.2=0.67[/math]\n*   The mole fraction of NO\u2082 is [math]0.4/1.2=0.33[/math]\n*   The concentration of N\u2082O\u2084 is [math]n=\\frac{PV}{RT}=\\frac{0.67*1atm}{(0.0821 L\u22c5atm/K\u22c5mol)*308K} = 0.026 M[/math]\n*   The concentration of NO\u2082 is [math]n=\\frac{PV}{RT}=\\frac{0.33*1atm}{(0.0821 L\u22c5atm/K\u22c5mol)*308K} = 0.013 M[/math]\n\n**2. Define Kc and write the formula**\n\n*   Kc is the equilibrium constant expressed in terms of concentrations.\n\n**3. Calculate Kc**\n\nNow, we can plug the equilibrium concentrations into the Kc expression:\n\n[math]K_c = \\frac{[NO_2]^2}{[N_2O_4]}[/math]\n\n[math]K_c = \\frac{(0.013)^2}{(0.026)} = 0.0065[/math]\n\nTherefore, the value of Kc at 35\u00b0C is approximately 0.0065.\n\n**Important Note:** When the problem gives pressure, it may be best to calculate Kp, the equilibrium constant with respect to partial pressures, and then use the relationship [math]K_p = K_c (RT)^{\\Delta n}[/math] to find Kc, where \u0394n is the change in the number of moles of gas in the reaction (products - reactants). However, here it is simpler to use the concentration of each molecule to calculate Kc directly.",
